    <h2 id="start">Starting a Garden</h2>
    <p>
      <br>
      <b>Choosing your type of garden - </b> Do you want to grow herbs, vegtables, flowers, a combination? There's a lot of options. While there's no wrong answer, do make sure to start small and with something you will find passion in attending to. 
      <br><br>
      <b>Decide on location - </b> When picking specific plants, it is important to consider if your garden's location can meet the plants needs. Watch your yard and take note of how much <a href="/sunlight">sunlight</a> each area gets, the type of soil, and the grade. Generally speaking, you will want to plant in a flat place with nutrient dense soil. Different plants will have different soil and sunlight needs. You can contact your county extensions office for soil testing and recommendations on how to improve it. You may also decide to plant in pots or raised beds. 
      <br><br>
      <b>Pick your plants - </b> This is the most exciting step! While considereing the limitations and resources of your garden, you still will find an abundance of options. Check out our <a href="plantSearch">plant search page</a> to find information of different plants, their care requirements, and links to buy seeds. Factors to consider include: 
      <br> Care Requirements, how much time will you be able to dedicate to your garden maintenance? 
      <br> Environmental Factors, consider the <a href="/sunlight">sun</a>, <a href="/fertilizer">soil</a>, <a href="/agr_zones">agricultural zone</a>, and season you are planting in. 
      <br> Personal Interest, what plants spark an excitement in you? Choosing plants which interest you will make gardening even more rewarding.  
      <br><br>
      <b>Start Planting - </b> Okay, this might actually be the most exciting step. You've scouted the best location, you've picked out the seeds or plants you want to grow, and now it's time to build the garden bed or pot your plants! Make sure to not over pack your soil, follow any instructions for seeds (paying particular mind to depth), and know that it's normal for plants to experience an initial transplant shock when replanted.
      <br> <br>
      <b>Care for your garden - </b> Now it's time to start focusing on garden maintenance. make sure to set up your <a href="/my_garden">watering and fertilizer schedule</a> so that you can keep track of your plants needs. For <a href="/diseases_pests_weeds">pests, diseases, and weeds</a>, remember that the best offense is a good defense! Consider mulching your beds and regularly check plants for signs of an infestation or disease. 
    </p>
   
